table-0818-782.caption: Coaching changes
data: ASU alum Smith was moved to director of athletic development for the school.
Brown's contract was not renewed after the Roadrunners finished 9–19.
Earlywine was informed his contract would not be renewed.
Cooley accepted the vacant job at Providence
FAMU replaced Harris with star alum Johnson.
Barnes was fired after four seasons at the conclusion of the 2010–11 regular season. Overall wins versus losses was the reason cited.
Hewitt was fired six years following his lone Final Four appearance. Brian Gregory from Dayton was hired.
Hunter left for Georgia State after 17 years.
The school decided not to renew Ingle or his staff to help turn around the team's academic performance.
Williams retired at the end of the season after 22 years and a 461-252 (.646) record at his alma mater.
Haith left for the open Missouri job.
Arkansas hired former Nolan Richardson assistant Anderson.
Calloway resigned under pressure, effective at the end of the season.
Kennedy left for the opening at Texas A&M. Steve Prohm had been an assistant coach at Murray State and was promoted on May 23 to be their new head coach.
Wolfpack alum Lowe resigned after failing to make the NCAA Tournament in his five-year tenure.
Capel was fired just two years removed from an Elite Eight finish.
Asbury retired, turning the Waves program over to Associate Head Coach Wilson.
Johnson left for the open Fairfield Job
Davis was fired after only three seasons.

Greenberg was fired following a 5-24 season and after sitting out the final four games of the season for NCAA violations. In February 2012, he would be hit with a five-year show-cause penalty for misleading NCAA investigators.
Waugh resigned after guiding the Hatters to only two winning seasons in 10+ years as coach.
Sutton retired and was replaced by top assistant Payne.
Turgeon left in May for the Maryland job.
Clark was fired after finishing 10–21 in his fourth season. Athletic director Tim Fitzpatrick claimed that success for the men's basketball program is "critically important."
Fired on March 7, 2011 after finishing the regular season 13-18 and missing NCAA tournament. Stated in preseason that he should lose his job if Texas Tech missed the NCAA tournament again.
Announced on March 7, 2011, after finishing the regular season with a 4–26 record that included 19 straight losses.
Kruger left for Oklahoma after reportedly turning the job down.

Announced on March 12, 2011, After consecutive losing seasons, Boylen was relieved of his duties. Utah finished with a 13-18 overall record (6-10 MWC), the second-straight losing season for the Utes, who were 14-17 in 2009-10.
Homer's son, Bryce, had served as the associate head coach for a number of years prior to taking over the program in May 2011.
Schroyer was the first coach fired during the season as he was let go on February 7, 2011 following a 8-15 start.

table-0818-652.caption: Establishment of the company
data: 15 November - Registration of The Union Steel Corp. of SA Ltd.
1 September - Casting of South Africa's first steel at USCO.
Vereeniging Works commissioned.The Transvaal Blast Furnace Co. Ltd. is formed.A blast furnace is erected in Vereeniging.
March - Newcastle Works commissioned. A public company - the Newcastle Iron & Steel Works Ltd. formed.
South African Iron and Steel Industry Act, No. 11 of 1928 passed. 5 June - The South African Iron and Steel Industrial Corp. constituted under the Act. Iscor founded as a statutory parastatal.
4 April - The first steel is tapped from the open-hearth furnace at the Pretoria Works.
The African Metals Corp. (Amcor) established near Vereeniging.
Iscor company established to meet the increasing demand for steel in South Africa.
Commissioning of a plate mill at Vanderbijlpark Works.
Acquisition of a site of 97 square kilometre on the Vaal River.

Vanderbijlpark Works develops into a full-fledged integrated steelworks processing iron ore and other raw materials from mines throughout Southern Africa into hot-rolled, cold-rolled, galvanised and tinned sheets and coils.
4 October - Vanderbijlpark Works officially opened by His Excellency the Governor General, Dr E.G. Jansen.
May - the South African Government and Iscor decide to build a third integrated works at Newcastle.
17 March - first steel was made at Newcastle Works.
South African government commits itself to transferring certain state interests to the private sector.
Iscor closes two oldest blast furnaces at Pretoria Works.
November - Iscor Ltd. shares listed in the Steel and Allied sector of the Johannesburg Stock Exchange.
Iscor buys USCO's steel division in mid-1991.
Iscor, together with the Industrial Development Corp. (IDC), decides to pursue the Saldanha Steel project in the Western Cape.
Iscor unbundled to form the steel group, - called Iscor, and a mining company called Kumba Resources.
22 November - Iscor enters into a three-year business assistance agreement (BAA) with Anglo-Dutch steel producer LNM Holdings N.V.
15 January - Iscor Ltd. shareholders approve the business assistance agreement with LNM.
12 February - Minority shareholders in Iscor Ltd give LNM the go-ahead to proceed with a R1.8-billion partial offer.
17 August - LNM acquires controlling stake in Iscor. Iscor Ltd. renamed Ispat Iscor Ltd. and registered with the Registrar of Companies.

December - Ispat International NV acquires LNM Holdings NV, the parent company of Ispat Iscor. Merged company’s rename Mittal Steel Company NV. Mittal Steel merger with International Steel Group of the US, to create the world’s largest steel-maker.
14 March - Ispat commences trading under the name Mittal Steel Ltd.

table-0818-511.pgTitle: List of Atlantic hurricanes in the 18th century
table-0818-511.caption: 1780s
data: Charleston saw excessive rain and wind with the cyclone. Winds shifted from northwest to northeast as the storm passed offshore. Extensive damage was seen in North Carolina. Richmond saw violent northeast gusts for 24 hours, but no damage. Norfolk and Portsmouth reported a "25foot tide" which caused damage
One of the few hurricanes on record in the state

Led to the "highest tide ever before known in Norfolk." It struck the lower Chesapeake Bay. Portsmouth experienced a strong northeast to northwest gale for 3days. The storm in Virginia was noted in both the Virginia Gazette of October 1, and the New Jersey Gazette of October 1 (from Ludlum 1963 p.30). The Annual Register the next year reported that several ships had been driven ashore by the tide and the wind, with a total damage estimated at around £30,000.

San Lupo Hurricane - devastated agricultural fields. Governor Juan Dabán visited the islands affected area to inspect and help with the damages; it was the first time a governor of Puerto Rico did that after a Hurricane.

Heavy rainfall accompanied the storm. According to George Washington, tides were "occasionally high" at Mount Vernon, with "high freshes." James Madison at Montpelier saw the Rapidan River overflow its banks. The center may have passed very near his location, as the winds shifted from southeast to southwest.
It has been identified as ‘Event 6’ in Belizean sedimentary records by McCloskey and Keller. Several injuries were caused by this hurricane in Vera Cruz.
A storm moved just offshore the Georgia and South Carolina coastline to lead to a storm surge that caused 23people to perish, as well as flooding and crop damage between Savannah and Georgetown.

George Washington reported from Mount Vernon a "very high northeast wind" the previous night, which sank ships and blew down trees. A "more violent and severe a hurricane than for many years." Madison at Montpelier reports a "great wind and rain." According to the Philadelphia Independent Gazette on August 8, the storm in Norfolk began from the northeast at 5 p.m. on the 23rd, then blew a "perfect hurricane" from the south at 12:30 a.m.. The tide was lower than in 1785. Alexandria also saw the winds switch from east-northeast to south, which caused the highest known tide in the Potomac (from Ludlum 1963, p.30-31).

table-0818-101.caption: Main characters
data: Self-proclaimed "mascot" of the show, Tico is Rigodon's best friend and former partner in the circus. The pair are inseparable, but Rigodon was forced to hide Tico from Mr. Fog at first, concealing the small hamster (he has a hamster's tail instead of a mouse's, which means he can't be a mouse) within his travelling bag until their journey was underway. Tico is well known for his epic appetite, and is rarely seen without his "sun-clock", an archaeological artifact gifted to him early on the trip that uses the sun to tell time. Tico is the only case in which the original version and English-language dub differ on a character's nationality: in the original version, he is Spanish, while in the dub, he is Italian.

Transfer is a gray wolf, hired to sabotage Fog's journey by his rival, Mr. Sullivan. Throughout the series, he employs a variety of tactics to delay Fog and his party, ranging from leading them in the wrong direction to deliberately causing accidents. He is a master of disguise and can imitate perfectly the voices and mannerisms of those he is impersonating - but the audience can always identify him by his strange, glowing left eye.

table-0818-509.pgTitle: List of Atlantic hurricanes in the 18th century
data: A "severe equinoctial storm" made a breach through the Outer Banks of North Carolina eight miles above its present entrance near haul-over, and it was named New Inlet. This inlet was subsequently closed in 1881, costing $600,000 in that year's dollars.

Five ships were destroyed, but the crew and items were saved. A Spanish mission named Nuestra Senora De la Luz and the presidio San Augustine de Ahumado on the lower Trinity River was destroyed. Constance Bayou in Louisiana was named after one of the wrecked ships from this storm.
Destroyed half the town and many ships.
Sunk one ship, killing the entire crew except for three.
Destroyed 96 public buildings and 4048 houses. Appeared to pass over the island from west to east.
